her, are also considered relevant.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Cost Statement\"<|>\"formulas\"<|>\"A cost statement is a detailed breakdown of all costs associated with a particular project or contract. It includes both direct and indirect costs and is used to determine the minimum cost that should be charged for the contract.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Minimum Cost Calculation\"<|>\"formulas\"<|>\"The minimum cost calculation involves summing up all relevant costs to determine the lowest price at which a contract can be offered without incurring a loss. This includes costs such as training, handsets, control systems, and cables, while excluding sunk costs and non-incremental costs.\")**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"System Trainer\"<|>\"Relevant Costing Principles\"<|>\"The commission of $125 for each day spent delivering training at a client's site is a relevant cost because it is an incremental cost directly associated with the contract.\"**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Telephone Handsets\"<|>\"Relevant Costing Principles\"<|>\"The cost of the telephone handsets is relevant because the handsets are in regular use and will need to be replaced if used for the contract. Therefore, the current purchase price is considered.\"**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Swipe 2\"<|>\"Relevant Costing Principles\"<|>\"The cost of Swipe 2 is relevant because it represents the current market price of the control system required for the contract.\"**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Swipe 1\"<|>\"Relevant Costing Principles\"<|>\"The cost of modifying Swipe 1 and its opportunity cost of $3,000 are relevant because they represent the costs directly associated with using Swipe 1 for the contract.\"**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Cable\"<|>\"Relevant Costing Principles\"<|>\"The cost of the cable is relevant because it is frequently used by T Co, and the current market price must be considered for the contract.\"**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Cost Statement\"<|>\"Minimum Cost Calculation\"<|>\"The cost statement is used to